<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Supplementary written evidence for the Joint Committee on the draft Deregulation Bill: clause 47(3)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.55pt; text-indent:-42.55pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">UK Environmental Law Association – Supplementary written evidence</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Supplementary written evidence for the Joint Committee on the draft Deregulation Bill: clause 47(3)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Introductory comments</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 32.86pt; padding-left:2.84pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The UK Environmental Law Association </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">aims to make the law work for a better environment and to improve understanding and awareness of environmental law.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">UKELA’s members are involved in the pra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ctice, study or formulation of environmental l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">aw in the UK and the European Union. It attracts both lawyers and non-lawyers and has a broad membership from the private and public sectors.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This evidence supplements </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">UKELA’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> written submission on the draft Deregulation Bill dated 26</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">September, and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">oral evidence given by UKELA member Angus Evers to the Joint Committee on Wednesday 23</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">rd</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> October</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">That evidence concerned clauses 27 to 30 and clause 58, following a request for comments on those particular provisions by staff of the Joint Committee.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This supplementary evidence concerns clause 47(3). At the session on 23</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">rd</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> October, Committee members sought views on whether the provision would comply with the Aarhus Convention. UKELA had not previously considered the provision, so was not in a position to provide comments at that time.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Comments on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Compatibility of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Clause 47</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">(3) with the Aarhus Convention</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 32.86pt; padding-left:2.84pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Clause 47(3) povides for the repeal or modification of certain provisions of primary legislation as set out in Schedule 15, so as to remove consultation requirements.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 32.86pt; padding-left:2.84pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">UKELA considers that most of these provisions are unlikely to engage much public participation anyway and may not fall within the requirements of Articles 6,7 or 8 of the Aarhus Convention.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 32.86pt; padding-left:2.84pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">However, UKELA considers that some of the Environment Act 1995 provisions would meet the criteria</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">: i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n particular, the requirement under section 99 of the Environment Act 1995</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">for the Minister to consult Natural England and/or the Historic Buildings and Monuments Commission for England.  Since this provision relates to the passing of subordinate legislation relating inter alia to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“the conservation or enhancement of the natural beauty or amenity of the countryside</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">” and given that Article 8 of the Aarhus Convention states in relation to </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">PUBLIC PARTICIPATION DURING THE PREPARATION OF EXECUTIVE REGULATIONS AND/OR GENERALLY APPLICABLE LEGALLY BINDING NORMATIVE INSTRUMENTS</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Each Party shall strive to promote effective public participation at an appropriate stage, and while options are still open, during the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">preparation by public authorities of executive regulations and other generally applicable legally binding rules that may have a significant effect on the environment.  …</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the repeal of this provision</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> would seem to represent a threat to compliance with the UK’s obligations under Aarhus.  </span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 32.86pt; padding-left:2.84pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Mor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">eover, since the powers under section </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">99 extend to the making or modifying of subordinate legislation (which surely qualifies as “executive regulation and/or generally applicable legally binding normative instruments”) it seems very unlikely that any other, prior, public participation would have taken place other than in general terms</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. Accordingly, if this requirement were repealed, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">legislation with the potential profoundly to affect the landscape or conservation could be passed without any meaningful public participation in the process.  This would be contrary to recent opinions from the Aarhus Compliance Committee and in particular the guidance issued in the “Moray Feu Traffic scheme” application (ACCC/C/2010/53) where something as lowly as a Traffic Regulation Order was considered to be subordinate legislation captured by the terms of Article 8.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 32.86pt; padding-left:2.84pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It seems that “effective public participation” in the formulation of these measures is necessary and, moreover, it should take plac</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e at an “early stage”.  Since section </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">99 of the EA 1995 confers the power to create regulation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ab initio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> it is unlikely that any prior participation in respect of it will have taken place.  </span><a name="_GoBack"></a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">29</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> October 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa